"sectionName":"Sport","sectionId":"sport","id":"sport/2014/nov/29/shane-sutton-gb-london-track-world-cup-cycling","fields":{"shortUrl":"http://gu.com/p/43yz3","standfirst":"<p>London track World Cup at the Pringle is the start for riders aiming to reach Rio Olympics in 2016<br>• <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/sport/2014/mar/03/shane-sutton-team-gb-world-track-championships\">GB’s poor performance at world championship</a><br>•<a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/sport/2014/mar/01/joanna-rowsell-gold-track-cycling-world-championships-cali-colombia\"> Joanna Rowsell wins gold in Colombia</a><br>• <a href=\"www.theguardian.com/sport/2014/apr/12/shane-sutton-complete-coach-reinvigorate-team-gb\">Shane Sutton succeeds David Brailsford</a></p>","hasStoryPackage":"false","body":"<p>Two years passes surprisingly quickly, hence the significance of the <a href=\"http://www.trackworldcup.co.uk/Schedule\" title=\"\">London track World Cup</a> that starts on Friday. It would be an exaggeration to say that for Great Britain’s cyclists the road to Rio will begin when the flag falls on the first race at the velodrome in the Olympic Park, but the timescale does not lie: the midpoint in the Olympic cycle is past, and the countdown is on.</p> <p>For the new man at the helm of British Cycling, Shane Sutton, the World Cup is about “managing expectations”. It is an intriguing cocktail: the high-profile nature of the London event, its evocative location in the Pringle, its timing in the season and the background of <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/sport/2014/mar/03/shane-sutton-team-gb-world-track-championships\" title=\"\">February’s world championships, the worst in terms of results in recent years</a>. “The riders will want success in front of their home crowd but ultimately it’s about Olympic qualification, so it’s about securing points and if wins come on the back of that then fantastic,” Sutton says.</p> <p>“Everyone is going to be living off what happened in London [in 2012] and the public will expect, but that’s part and parcel of elite sport. We were a force in London, and we want to be a force in Rio, but this is part of the pathway to get there. A lot of people are in heavy work still and this isn’t something we can taper for, given we want to go and have a successful Worlds. We can’t be at our optimum. There’s a lot of people doubting us after what happened in Colombia, but we can see a trend and we will be competitive across the board.”</p> <p><a href=\"http://\" title=\"\">The 57-year-old Australian took over from Sir Dave Brailsford</a> in mid-April after two Olympic cycles as Brailsford’s right-hand man. In some ways the succession seems like a poisoned chalice. Expectations remain sky high after the London Games but that ignores certain facts. Part of the London gold rush was dependent on two riders at the end of their careers – Sir Chris Hoy and Victoria Pendleton. Brailsford and Sutton’s intense focus between Beijing and London, first on setting up Team Sky and then getting through the home Games, was not conducive to long-term thinking. Between 2008 and 2013 there was a brain drain, with several key coaches – Scott Gardner at sprint, Matt Parker and Dan Hunt at endurance – leaving for other sports.</p> <p>That helps explain, in part, the disaster that was the world championships in Cali. Although the women won five medals – with two golds for <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/sport/2014/nov/27/shane-sutton-joanna-rowsell-spoty\" title=\"\">Joanna Rowsell</a> – for the first time since 1998, the men returned empty handed, outshone by the Irish, who have no velodrome and minimal funding. Sutton puts that down to the remaining hangover from the Olympics. “It was tall building [syndrome]. They had to get themselves so high for London that when it finished they crashed and burned because they’d given everything. It’s taken a while to bounce back from that.</p> <p>“We sat down and looked at ourselves and re-addressed our philosophy. I said we needed to freshen up and we’ve done that. I’ve seen changes. I wouldn’t say the riders weren’t committed but after the success in London there were a lot of distractions. The riders have a certain amount of earning potential and limited time to capitalise on that. We always said the best time for that was the two years after the Games and then they need to start on the road to Rio.”</p> <p>The changes have come apace. Heiko Salzwedel, one of the best endurance coaches in the world who worked wonders on small budgets with Switzerland and Denmark, has been persuaded to return for a third spell in Britain, with “a clean sheet of paper” to work off. Below him, the endurance coaches have been reshuffled, with Paul Manning returning to supervise the women. A new sprint coach, Justin Grace, has been added to the team. A new mountain bike coach is being sought. Further down the ladder the talent development system has been revised.</p> <p>In the short term, Sutton wants his coaches to be “Rio ready” by New Years’ Day, with all the structures in place for the run-in to the Olympics. He also has very specific problems to contend with. A replacement is urgently needed for Hoy in the Man Three position in the men’s team sprint, although Callum Skinner, another Scot, has recently made promising strides. In the women’s sprint, Becky James appeared certain to take over from Pendleton after taking four medals at the 2013 Worlds in Minsk, <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/sport/2014/oct/25/becky-james-2016-olympics-injuries-surgery-rio\" title=\"\">but she has been ruled out at least for this season with a severe knee injury</a>, and her return date is unknown.</p> <p>Alongside the sprint conundrum, there are the small matters of managing Sir Bradley Wiggins’s return to the track midway through next year – with the foundation of “Team Wiggo” to include the bulk of his fellow potential team pursuiters – and persuading Mark Cavendish or Ben Swift to take a brief break from professional road racing to ride the omnium. <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/sport/2014/nov/26/mark-cavendish-never-taken-tour-de-france-for-granted-interview\" title=\"\">Cavendish has said he feels he could win the omnium, but is undecided</a>.</p> <p>“The ball is in their court,” says Sutton. “When you see the way Cav has been whizzing round Ghent and Zurich I’m sure it has whetted his appetite. All he needs to know is that GB is there for him.”</p> <p>Sutton’s long-term goal is “a full British coaching structure by the time I call it a day” – and currently he has his eyes on continuing to Tokyo in 2020, which is “not far away”. In the medium-term, he is looking to expand the women’s endurance academy and possibly return it to its former Belgian base. He would also like to see the men’s under-23 academy return to Europe.</p> <p>“We need to go back to the structure that worked in the past. We need to scour the world and find the right person. It needs to be done abroad because you take away the home comforts and they just have to ride their bikes.”</p>","headline":"Shane Sutton takes long-term view in order to repeat Team GB’s glory","trailText":"London track World Cup at the Pringle is the start for riders aiming to reach Rio Olympics in 2016","thumbnail":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2014/11/29/1417263449257/e3a29624-1eaf-4ec8-bb02-b3db503b195a-140x84.jpeg","wordcount":"1008","commentable":"false","byline":"William Fotheringham","productionOffice":"UK","liveBloggingNow":"false","commentCloseDate":"2014-12-02T12:00:02Z"},"webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/sport/2014/nov/29/shane-sutton-gb-london-track-world-cup-cycling","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/sport/2014/nov/29/shane-sutton-gb-london-track-world-cup-cycling","tags":[{"id":"sport/shane-sutton","webTitle":"Shane Sutton","type":"keyword","sectionId":"sport","sectionName":"Sport","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/sport/shane-sutton","apiUrl":"http: