n has long way to go to become a cycling nation","webPublicationDate":"2014-06-15T15:07:21Z","sectionName":"Life and style","sectionId":"lifeandstyle","id":"sport/2014/jun/15/chris-hoy-cycling-safety-britain","fields":{"shortUrl":"http://gu.com/p/3q5t9","standfirst":"Olympic gold medallist says UK lags behind Denmark, Germany and Netherlands on cycling safety and calls on politicians to act","hasStoryPackage":"true","body":"<p>Sir Chris Hoy has said Britain has a \"massive way\" to go until it becomes a fully fledged cycling nation, and fears it could take more deaths in road accidents for politicians to take action to improve cycling safety.</p><p>The six-times Olympic champion said the UK was heading in the right direction on cycling safety  but that the current climate could be holding back change. \"There can always be more done to improve safety on the roads. It has become an issue because of the popularity of cycling – in a way it takes headlines and awful accidents to really get the attention of the people that can make these decisions that can improve the environment for cycling,\" he said.</p><p>\"I remember [former Olympic champion] Chris Boardman saying change is painful and takes time and it's not going to be an easy process and I think he's absolutely right. To get to the stage where we're like Holland, Denmark or Germany where cycling is integrated into road provision, where there are plans put into place for cycling, where there are bike paths, junctions that are thoughtful for all traffic users, that will take time.\"</p><p>A huge surge in cycling popularity in recent years has resulted in almost half of the British population now owning a bike, more than 3 million people cycling at least three times a week and 750,000 people commuting to work on bikes, up from 90,000 in 2001, according to the census.</p><p>Hoy, who was <a href=\"http://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/chris-hoy-more-cyclists-will-die-before-action-is-taken-by-mps-9537545.html\" title=\"\">speaking to the Independent on Sunday</a> at the launch of his own range of bikes, said  the conversation had changed as cycling safety moved up the agenda.</p><p>\"When the people in power realise the benefits of cycling in terms of reducing congestion and improving the health of the nation it seems like an obvious thing to do – but then I'm a cyclist. You want everyone – cyclists and drivers – to get from A to B as safely as possible,\" he said. \"Just the very fact that it's being discussed in the national press is a good start – we are getting somewhere but there is still a massive way to go.</p><p>\"We are a very congested small island, but all the more reason to putting cycling at the forefront. We can reduce the number of other vehicles on the road and get more bikes on the road.\"</p><p>In 2012, more than 3,200 cyclists were seriously injured on the road. There were 122 deaths including 13 children – a five-year high. Figures for 2013 are due in the coming weeks, and cycling safety groups will be pushing for further measures to make Britain's roads safer.</p><p>Speaking before the Tour de France, <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2014/apr/19/tour-de-france-yorkshire\" title=\"\">which begins on 5 July  in Yorkshire</a>, Hoy questioned why  former team-mate Bradley Wiggins  was being left out of the Tour de France lineup.</p><p>\"Everyone's disappointed. Everyone would love to see Bradley racing in the UK in the Tour but I suppose what we don't know is what goes on behind the scene with managers and inter-team relationship,\" he said.</p><p>\"Dave [Sir Dave Brailsford, the former British Cycling performance director now Team Sky general manager] must have decided the best chance of winning the Tour was with someone other than Bradley, which seems amazing when you think about it: how can you leave out someone with his pedigree and performance?\"</p><p>He added: \"But there's always method in Dave's madness. It's not to say he couldn't win it with Bradley, absolutely not, all teams would be crying out for someone like Bradley on their team but Dave has made that call with Chris Froome and the team around Chris that he feels can best support him to win the tour. It is a shame for the fans but sport is ruthless.</p><p>\"If Chris Froome is in yellow on the last day on the Champs Elysée I think people will forget that and say it was the right call to make.\"</p>","headline":"Chris Hoy: Britain has long way to go to become a cycling nation","trailText":"Olympic gold medallist says UK lags behind Denmark, Germany and Netherlands on cycling safety and calls on politicians to act","thumbnail":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2014/6/15/1402844404276/-Sir-Chris-Hoy-006.jpg","wordcount":"647","commentable":"true","byline":"Alexandra Topping","productionOffice":"UK","liveBloggingNow":"false","commentCloseDate":"2014-06-18T15:07:21Z"},"webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/sport/2014/jun/15/chris-hoy-cycling-safety-britain","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/sport/2014/jun/15/chris-hoy-cycling-safety-britain","tags":[{"id":"lifeandstyle/cycling","webTitle":"Cycling","type":"keyword","sectionId":"lifeandstyle","sectionName":"Life and style","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/cycling","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/lifeandstyle/cycling","references":[]},{"id":"sport/cycling","webTitle":"Cycling","type":"keyword","sectionId":"sport","sectionName":"Sport","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/sport/cycling","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/sport/cycling","references":[]},{"id":"sport/chrishoy","webTitle":"Sir Chris Hoy","type":"keyword","sectionId":"sport","sectionName":"Sport","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/sport/chrishoy","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/sport/chrishoy","references":[]},{"id":"sport/sport","webTitle":"Sport","type":"keyword","sectionId":"sport","sectionName":"Sport","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/sport/sport","